    "43741671": {
      "title": "A technique to investigate surface morphology and endothelial cell replication of small arteries: A study in acute angiotenSin-induced hypertensive rats",
      "abstract": "Abstract A technique was developed for exposing the luminal surface of small blood vessels and viewing their endothelium by scanning electron microscopy. This technique, used in conjunction with conventional autoradiographic procedures, was also used to identify replicating endothelial cells. Rats were injected (iv) with angiotensin II (5 μg every 7 min) for 2 or 4 hr, while control animals received saline. In the angiotensin animals, blood pressure rose to 180–220 mm Hg. After 4 hr of angiotensin II infusion, focal regions of endothelial cell denudation and platelet adherence to the subendothelium were observed in small mesenteric arteries. These vessels also appeared contracted and endothelial cells exhibited loss of intracellular structure, swollen mitochondria, and loss of intercellular junctions. Small clusters of platelets were frequently observed adhering to an apparently intact endothelium both after 2 and 4 hr of intermittent angiotensin II infusiuon but were not seen in the saline controls. Although replicating endothelial cells were not observed in the angiotensin II-treated vessels, endothelial cell replication was found in controls where the vessels were mechanically injured."
    }
  },
